23 SECTION 13. IC 20-26-7-47, AS AMENDED BY P.L.36-2024,
24 SECTION 2, IS AMENDED TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
25 UPON PASSAGE]: Sec. 47. (a) The following definitions apply
26 throughout this section:
27 (1) "Covered school building" has the meaning set forth in
28 IC 20-26-7.1-2.1.
29 (2) "Current school year" refers to a year in which the governing
30 body is required to conduct a review of school building usage
31 under subsection (c).
32 (3) "Enrollment" refers to the following:
33 (A) Except as provided in clause (B), students counted in
34 ADM (as defined in IC 20-43-1-6) in the first count date for a
35 school year fixed under IC 20-43-4-3.
36 (B) With regard to a school corporation, students counted in a
37 school corporation's fall count of ADM minus all students
38 counted in the fall count of ADM who are enrolled in eligible
39 schools that:
40 (i) have entered into an agreement with the school
41 corporation to participate as a participating innovation
42 network charter school under IC 20-25.7-5; and
HB 1423—LS 7118/DI 110

24
1 (ii) are included in the school corporation's fall ADM count.
2 (4) "Interested person" has the meaning set forth in
3 IC 20-26-7.1-2.2.
4 (b) This section:
5 (1) applies to a school corporation only if:
6 (1) (A) the total student enrollment for in-person instruction in
7 the school corporation in the current school year is at least ten
8 percent (10%) less than the student enrollment for in-person
9 instruction in the school corporation in a school year that
10 precedes the current school year by five (5); and
11 (2) (B) the school corporation in the current school year has
12 more than one (1) school building serving the same grade level
13 as the school building subject to closure under this section;
14 and
15 (2) does not apply to a school city (as defined in
16 IC 20-25-2-12).
17 (c) Each school year, the governing body of a school corporation
18 shall review the usage of school buildings used by the school
19 corporation to determine whether any school building should be closed
20 for the ensuing school year and subsequent school years.
21 (d) A school corporation shall close a school building for the
22 ensuing school year (and subsequent school years) if:
23 (1) at any time the school building had been used for classroom
24 instruction;
25 (2) in the current school year and the two (2) school years
26 immediately preceding the current school year the school building
27 was underutilized for classroom instruction purposes or other
28 allowable uses specified by this section;
29 (3) as of the end of the school year before the school building is
30 required to be closed under this section, the school corporation
31 was not subject to a transitional plan adopted by the governing
32 body and approved by the department to use the school building
33 for an allowable use not later than the next school year after the
34 school building is otherwise required to be closed under this
35 section;
36 (4) in the case of a school building that was used in any part in the
37 current school year for instructional purposes, the school
38 corporation has another school building:
39 (A) with sufficient capacity to take the students using the
40 school building being considered for closure; and
41 (B) that does not require more than twenty (20) minutes of
42 travel time by car or bus from the school building being
HB 1423—LS 7118/DI 110

25
1 considered for closure; and
2 (5) the school building is not a school building described in
3 IC 20-26-7.1-1, IC 20-26-7.1-3(b), IC 20-26-7.1-3(c), or
4 IC 20-26-7.1-3(d).
5 (e) For purposes of this section, a school building is underutilized
6 in a school year if the school building is not used for any of the
7 following allowable uses:
8 (1) The number of full-time equivalent students enrolled for
9 in-person instruction in the school building on instructional days
10 (as determined under IC 20-30-2) for instructional purposes,
11 averaged over the current school year and the two (2) school years
12 immediately preceding the current school year, is at least fifty
13 percent (50%) of:
14 (A) the known classroom design capacity of the school
15 building; or
16 (B) if the design capacity is not known, the average maximum
17 full-time equivalent enrollment in any of the last twenty-five
18 (25) years, as validated by records created or maintained by
19 the department.
20 (2) The school corporation demonstrates through facts included
21 in a resolution that the school building is being used and that it is
22 financially prudent to continue to use the school building,
23 considering all community resources, for a distinct student
24 population that reasonably cannot be served through integration
25 with the general school population, such as students attending an
26 alternative education program (as defined in IC 20-30-8-1).
27 However, to be an allowable use under this subdivision, the
28 average number of full-time equivalent students using the school
29 building in a school year for instructional purposes must be at
30 least thirty percent (30%) of:
31 (A) the known classroom design capacity of the school
32 building; or
33 (B) if the design capacity is not known, the average maximum
34 full-time equivalent enrollment in any of the last twenty-five
35 (25) years, as validated by records created or maintained by
36 the department; and
37 (if multiple school buildings are used for the same purposes)
38 combining the student populations into fewer school buildings is
39 not reasonably feasible.
40 (3) The school corporation demonstrates through facts included
41 in a resolution that the school building is being used and that it is
42 financially prudent to continue to use the school building,
HB 1423—LS 7118/DI 110

26
1 considering all community resources, for administrative or other
2 school offices. However, to be an allowable use under this
3 subdivision, at least fifty percent (50%) of the square footage of
4 the school building must be used for offices, the personnel
5 headquartered in the school building must consistently use the
6 space for office purposes, and the occupancy cost of using the
7 school building cannot be more than comparable office space that
8 is available in the school district.
9 (4) The school corporation demonstrates through facts included
10 in a resolution that the school building is being used and that it is
11 financially prudent to continue to use the school building,
12 considering all community resources, for storage. However, to be
13 an allowable use under this subdivision, at least fifty percent
14 (50%) of the square footage of the school building must be used
15 for storage, on average the storage space must be used to capacity,
16 and the cost of using the school building for storage must be less
17 than comparable storage space that is available in the school
18 district.
19 (5) The school corporation demonstrates through facts included
20 in a resolution that the school building is being used and that it is
21 financially prudent to continue to use the school building,
22 considering all community resources, for a combination of office
23 space and storage. However, to be an allowable use under this
24 subdivision, at least fifty percent (50%) of the square footage of
25 the school building must be used for a combination of office
26 space and storage and:
27 (A) the personnel headquartered in the school building must
28 consistently use the office space for office purposes, and the
29 occupancy cost of using the office space, calculated using the
30 costs of operating the school building, cannot be more than
31 comparable office space that is available in the school district;
32 and
33 (B) on average, the storage space must be used to capacity and
34 the cost of using the school building for storage must be less
35 than comparable storage space that is available in the school
36 district.
37 (f) Closure of a school building that is:
38 (1) owned by the school corporation or any other entity that is
39 related in any way to, or created by, the school corporation or the
40 governing body; or
41 (2) jointly owned in the same manner by two (2) or more school
42 corporations;
HB 1423—LS 7118/DI 110

27
1 shall be carried out in conformity with IC 20-26-7.1.
2 (g) Before filing a petition under subsection (h), a charter school or
3 state educational institution that is interested in a school corporation's
4 school building must give written notice to the school corporation to
5 determine whether an agreement can be reached regarding the school
6 corporation making the school building available for lease or purchase
7 under IC 20-26-7.1.
8 (h) If an agreement is not reached within forty-five (45) days after
9 the date that the school corporation receives the notice under
10 subsection (g), the charter school or state educational institution may
11 petition the department to initiate or the department on its own may
12 initiate a proceeding for a determination as to whether a school
13 building meets the criteria for closure under this section or a covered
14 school building that is no longer used for classroom instruction by a
15 school corporation should be made available under IC 20-26-7.1. If a
16 charter school or state educational institution petitions the department
17 under this subsection, the charter school or state educational institution
18 must provide a copy of the petition to the applicable school
19 corporation.
20 (i) An interested person that is not otherwise a party to the
21 proceeding may intervene in the proceeding under subsection (h) as a
22 party. The school corporation has the burden of going forward with the
23 evidence and the burden of proof to demonstrate that the school
24 building does not meet the criteria for closure or the covered school
25 building is not required to be made available under IC 20-26-7.1.
26 (j) Not more than sixty (60) days after receiving notice of a petition
27 under subsection (h), the school corporation must:
28 (1) file a response to the petition that notifies the department that
29 the school corporation:
30 (A) is not contesting the petition; or
31 (B) is contesting the petition and states the facts upon which
32 the school corporation relies in contesting the petition; and
33 (2) provide a copy of the response to the petitioner and any
34 intervening party.
35 (k) If the school corporation:
36 (1) files a response that the school corporation is not contesting
37 the petition; or
38 (2) fails to submit a timely response under subsection (j);
39 the department shall issue an order granting the petition. A petition and
40 any response or reply are public documents.
41 (l) If a school corporation contests a petition under subsection (j),
42 a party to the proceeding has not more than sixty (60) days after the
HB 1423—LS 7118/DI 110

28
1 date that the school corporation files a response under subsection (j) to
2 submit a reply to the school corporation's response.
3 (m) The department shall make a determination regarding a petition
4 under subsection (h) not more than one hundred twenty (120) days after
5 the date that the:
6 (1) petitioner and any intervening party have submitted a reply
7 under subsection (l); or
8 (2) time period to reply under subsection (l) has expired.
9 (n) A school corporation or another party to the proceeding may file
10 with the state board a petition requesting review of the department's
11 determination. Upon receipt of a petition under this subsection, the
12 state board shall review the department's determination. An appeal to
13 the state board shall be subject to the procedure described in
14 IC 20-26-11-15(b).
15 (o) Upon the issuance of a final unappealable order granting a
16 petition, the school corporation shall make the school building
17 available for lease or purchase in accordance with IC 20-26-7.1.
